external_knowledge:
- "Navigated the stormy seas of high winds and clear skies" refers to researchers who accessed weather records with high wind speeds and good visibility;
- "Frequent access" is represented by the count of access events for each user;
- "During the year 2014" specifies the date range for the weather records.

- "weather enthusiasts" refers to users who have accessed weather records;
- "frequently delved into the records of the most scorching and frosty days" refers to users who have accessed records with the highest maximum temperatures and the lowest minimum temperatures;
- "explored these extremes" refers to the cumulative count of such accesses.

- "Chilly start" refers to a minimum temperature (`min_temp`) less than 10°C;
- "Warm end" refers to a maximum temperature (`max_temp`) greater than 20°C;
- "Top 3 warmest records" refers to the records with the highest maximum temperatures (`max_temp`) for each location.

sql:
SELECT min_temp, max_temp, atmospheric_pressure
FROM weather_records
WHERE record_id = 1;

SELECT date, min_temp, max_temp
FROM weather_records
WHERE record_id = 1;

